<span class='talk-transcript__para__text'>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='569011' id='t-569011'>Now, what this, even this brief debate, brings out</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='573832' id='t-573832'>is something that many economists overlook.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='577650' id='t-577650'>Economists often assume</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='579746' id='t-579746'>that markets are inert,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='582370' id='t-582370'>that they do not touch or taint the goods they exchange.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='586736' id='t-586736'>Market exchange, they assume,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='589840' id='t-589840'>doesn't change the meaning or value</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='592300' id='t-592300'>of the goods being exchanged.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='593583' id='t-593583'>This may be true enough</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='595159' id='t-595159'>if we're talking about material goods.</span>
